  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. International Developments\n- Formation of Financial Action Task Force (FATF) in 1989\n- Establishment of global anti-money laundering standards\n- Increased international collaboration and information sharing\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Enhanced due diligence regulations\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Enhanced Regulatory Frameworks\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Customer risk assessment protocols\n- Mandatory transaction monitoring systems\n- Stricter identification verification processes\n\n5. Digital Age Adaptations\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Online transaction tracking\n- Enhanced technological surveillance\n- Cross-border digital transaction monitoring\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Increased focus on complex financial networks\n- Artificial intelligence and machine learning integration\n- Stronger whistleblower protections\n\n7. Global Compliance Mechanisms\n- Regular international assessments\n- Standardized reporting protocols\n- Coordinated enforcement strategies\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve with emerging financial technologies and methods.",
